  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/Tengu/tengu-cockpit/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md', content='# ADR-076: Double-agent TDD flow\n\n- Status: Accepted\n- Date: 2026-04-23\n\n## Context\n\nD.U.H. already supports subagents (`Agent`, `Swarm`), a shared `Engine` loop, print-mode CLI entry points, slash commands, and a deterministic stub provider for tests. What it does not provide is a first-class workflow for disciplined pair-programming TDD where two cooperating agents must move through a strict red-green-refactor sequence.\n\nThe requested feature requires:\n\n- a real user-triggerable entry point,\n- strict six-phase ordering,\n- a clear contract between the two roles,\n- distinct handling for RED versus GREEN outcomes,\n- tests against a stubbed provider,\n- and documentation that matches the shipped UX.\n\n## Decision\n\nAdd a new public CLI subcommand: `duh tdd`.\n\n`duh tdd` will execute a dedicated orchestration layer that reuses existing D.U.H. abstractions:\n\n- `duh.agents.run_agent` for Driver/Navigator role turns,\n- existing provider/session wiring patterns where useful,\n- existing CLI parser/main dispatch,\n- and the existing stub provider for deterministic end-to-end tests.\n\nThe orchestration will live in a small dedicated module and model the workflow as explicit phases, not as free-form text prompting. The command will accept:\n\n- a task prompt,\n- a required test command,\n- optional driver/navigator agent types,\n- optional tier/model selections.\n\nThe orchestrator will run the six phases in strict order:\n\n1. Navigator drafts spec.\n2. Driver writes failing test, then the test command is executed and must fail.\n3. Driver writes minimal code, then the test command is executed and must pass.\n4. Navigator proposes refactor.\n5. Driver applies refactor.\n6. Navigator validates by re-running tests and checking the refactor outcome.\n\nIf RED unexpectedly passes, the flow does not advance to GREEN. Instead, Navigator is invoked again to tighten the spec and the flow reports a distinct `red_not_failing` outcome.\n\n## Driver/Navigator contract\n\n### Navigator responsibilities\n\n- Before RED: produce a tight test specification with expected behavior and failure target.\n- After GREEN: propose a concrete refactor that preserves behavior.\n- Final phase: validate that tests still pass and that the refactor was actually applied.\n\n### Driver responsibilities\n\n- RED: write the failing test that implements the Navigator spec.\n- GREEN: write the minimum production change needed for the test to pass.\n- REFACTOR: apply the Navigator’s refactor proposal without changing behavior.\n\n### Shared contract\n\n- Neither role may skip or reorder phases.\n- RED is successful only when the specified test command fails.\n- GREEN is successful only when the same command passes.\n- Validation is successful only when tests pass after the refactor and the refactor marker/check passes.\n- The orchestrator, not the model, is the source of truth for phase progression.\n\n## Design details\n\nImplement a `DoubleAgentTDDSession` orchestration object with:\n\n- explicit phase names/enums,\n- structured step results,\n- injectable `agent_runner` and `test_runner` dependencies for unit tests,\n- transcript capture for CLI rendering.\n\nThe CLI command will print phase headers and final outcome. Help text will document required flags.\n\nThe initial implementation will use a lightweight refactor-application check based on the Driver response being captured after the Navigator’s refactor suggestion and the final validation phase receiving that suggestion/result context. This keeps the implementation aligned with current D.U.H. abstractions without inventing new patch-tracking infrastructure.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\n### 1. Add the flow as a slash command only\n\nRejected. A slash command is useful later, but the task requires a real public feature and coherent `--help` output. A dedicated CLI subcommand is easier to document, test, and exercise end-to-end.\n\n### 2. Build the workflow entirely as one big prompt\n\nRejected. That would let the model decide whether to honor the sequence. The requirement is strict ordering, so phase control must be implemented in Python.\n\n### 3. Implement with `Swarm` parallelism\n\nRejected. The workflow is sequential by design. `Swarm` is the wrong abstraction for ordered red-green-refactor handoff.\n\n### 4. Add a bespoke agent runtime separate from `run_agent`\n\nRejected. Existing agent infrastructure already creates child `Engine` runs with role-specific prompts. Reusing it avoids duplicated provider/session logic.\n\n## Consequences\n\n### Positive\n\n- Strict phase ordering is enforced by code.\n- The feature reuses D.U.H.’s existing agent abstractions.\n- The flow is deterministic under unit tests because both agent and test execution can be injected/stubbed.\n- The UX is discoverable through `duh tdd --help`.\n\n### Negative\n\n- The first version adds a CLI-specific orchestration path rather than integrating directly into the REPL slash-command surface.\n- Refactor application validation is pragmatic rather than semantic; it validates via test pass + captured refactor execution context, not AST-level change analysis.\n\n## Follow-up\n\nPotential future work:\n\n- add `/tdd` slash-command parity,\n- render phase progress in the TUI,\n- enrich validation with changed-file inspection or patch assertions,\n- support automatic RED retries when the Navigator revises the spec.\n')
